values:
I&#39;m honestly not sure whether you use this or check it at all, kelly_joy, but if you do:


<span style="font-size:1.8em;">HAPPY BIRTHDAY!!</span>



I wish you all sorts of joyous happenings this year.&nbsp;

&nbsp; &nbsp; I&#39;ve just started watching <i>Smallville </i>- yes, I know, don&#39;t start.&nbsp; Ten seasons is lots to play with, and I like that.&nbsp; On the other hand, I keep wanting to yell at the characters to just pick up a fucking phone and call or text people when they need something or aren&#39;t going to be there.&nbsp; And then I remember: this is supposed to be small-town Kansas, and more importantly, it&#39;s 2002.&nbsp;
&nbsp; &nbsp; People just didn&#39;t text all that much...
&nbsp; &nbsp; I&#39;m used to it in shows I watched at the time: I can&#39;t imagine Buffy texting.&nbsp; But starting something that&#39;s new to me, and I feel as if they should have the tech.&nbsp; (Especially because it&#39;s 1989 when the Kents find Clark and his spaceship, but the high-school first season is just listed as &quot;today&quot;...)

&nbsp; &nbsp; I use To-Do lists a lot.&nbsp; I love scratching things off, but the list gets longer and the number of scratches is small compared to whatever needs doing in a day.&nbsp; I need to get back to &quot;attempting a reasonable number&quot; of tasks, rather than &quot;never getting it all done&quot;.&nbsp; &nbsp; Plus, at some point something happens that needs to go near the top of the list, but there isn&#39;t room, and then do you re-write or draw arrows or use numbers to indicate priority...?&nbsp; (No: I&#39;m not really asking advice.&nbsp; Just noting my own particular weirdness.)
&nbsp; &nbsp; Today, I wrote out the things I needed to get done today onto individual post-it notes.&nbsp; Four - and then one extra, so five - items.&nbsp; I stuck the notes on my fridge.&nbsp; And I kept seeing them, as I went back and forth, as I did other things.&nbsp; And over the afternoon, four of the five tasks got done and notes got taken off the fridge.&nbsp; Maybe the fifth tonight?&nbsp; Probably not, but it&#39;ll be there looking at me while I make tea in the morning, and I think that will be useful.
&nbsp; &nbsp; I don&#39;t like things stuck to my fridge, see. And I <i>do </i>like scrunching up paper and putting it in the recycling.&nbsp;

&nbsp; &nbsp; We&#39;ll see whether this works for more than a day...&nbsp; But I have hopes.&nbsp; I may keep a Master-list of To-Dos somewhere, that can get longer and longer and doesn&#39;t have to be in order, and then choose the X number of tasks to post on the fridge on a day.&nbsp;
&nbsp; &nbsp; Aren&#39;t you glad you asked?&nbsp;
&nbsp; &nbsp; Wait.&nbsp; You didn&#39;t.&nbsp; Hm.&nbsp; Aren&#39;t you glad I ramble...?

Today, of course, is Women&#39;s Remembrance Day in Canada, marking the date of the Montreal Massacre.&nbsp;

It&#39;s also the Fox&#39;s birthday.&nbsp; I understand he&#39;s flying back from Spain tomorrow or the next day.&nbsp; Looking forward to seeing him.&nbsp; Still so much fondness there.

The painting at my mom&#39;s place took many days, but not long ones: we did a coat on the walls, or a layer of trim, and then we&#39;d gift-shop or do some other non-house thing.&nbsp; It&#39;s been a good week.&nbsp; Today, we moved all of her stored furniture from my garage into her basement, which was heavy work, but she and I are good together with stuff like that, and it went well.&nbsp; Plus, the room looks great.&nbsp; It was such an ugly place before - both actively damp and poorly laid-out - and now it looks so fabulous that it&#39;s hard to remember.&nbsp; She has enough room to sleep all the guests she could want, as well as serious scrapping and storage space.&nbsp; She&#39;s really happy.&nbsp; And I&#39;m happy to have contributed to getting it ready, given how much work she put into my house.
